        output='Based on the provided text, here is what the filing discloses about Starship, organized by your requested categories:\n\n### Development Status\n*   **Current Testing:** The company has executed **11 Starship flight tests** to date and has scheduled a 12th flight test.\n*   **Next-Generation Debut:** The 12th flight test will debut the **next generation Starship vehicle and Super Heavy booster**, powered by the next evolution of the Raptor engine.\n*   **Current Classification:** Starship is a **fully reusable rocket** composed of boosters, ships, and Raptor engines and is **currently in the development stage**.\n*   **Key Milestone:** The company expects to achieve **commencement of payload delivery to orbit in 2026**.\n*   **Specific Requirements Noted:** Full reusability of Starship’s upper stage and in-orbit refueling are **not required** to deploy the next-generation V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites in low-Earth orbit.\n\n### Revenue Generation and Commercial Contracts\n*   **No Current Revenue:** The filing contains **no disclosure of any current revenue** being generated by Starship.\n*   **Contract Inclusion:** "Launch and Development" contracts, which can range from one to fourteen years, include work for government agency space programs utilizing Starship. However, the majority of Starship costs are currently expensed to Research and development as incurred.\n*   **Inter-segment Activity:** For internal Starlink satellite launches, the company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue. The filing does not disclose any external commercial Starship launch contracts.\n\n### Financial Treatment and Near-Term Revenue vs. Long-Duration Strategic Investment\nThe filing consistently frames Starship as a **long-duration strategic investment** that is a significant expense driver with no near-term revenue and will ultimately have a different financial treatment upon commercialization.\n\n*   **No Near-Term Revenue:** Starship is not generating revenue. Its development is materially increasing costs and reducing Segment Adjusted EBITDA in the Space segment.\n\n*   **Heavy R&D Expense (Not Capitalized):** A majority of Starship costs are **expensed to Research and development as incurred**. The Space segment\'s R&D expenses "mainly relate to the development, build, and testing of Starship."\n    *   In the three months ended March 31, 2026, the Space segment funded **$930 million** in R&D for the Starship program.\n    *   In the year ended December 31, 2025, the Space segment funded **$3,004 million** in R&D for the Starship program (a significant acceleration from $1,835 million in 2024).\n\n*   **Long-Duration Strategic Investment:** The filing explicitly states Starship is the **"key enabler of our long-term growth strategy by unlocking entirely new categories of missions."** The long-term vision includes point-to-point terrestrial travel, space tourism, in-orbit manufacturing, passenger/cargo transport to the Moon and Mars, and energy production on the Moon and Mars.\n\n*   **Future Capitalization:** The financial treatment of Starship will change upon commercialization. The filing states, **"At commercialization, Starship costs generally will be capitalized and then depreciated in cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload delivered."** This confirms the asset is a long-term investment that will shift from an expensed R&D cost to a capitalized asset on the balance sheet only when it becomes operational.\n\n### Material Disclosures Cited in Your Preamble\nAll of the material risks you outlined are confirmed in the filing:\n*   **Development delays materially impairing deployment:** Delays in Starship development would materially and adversely affect the ability to deploy next-generation V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, and orbital AI compute infrastructure, impacting revenue and growth.\n*   **Falcon Dependency:** The current operational rockets, Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy, "are not capable of deploying V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites," making Starship indispensable for these strategic initiatives.\n*   **Capital Investment Risk:** The development of Starship "will require the investment of significant additional capital resources," and prioritizing this long-term growth may reduce near-term profitability.',
