    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='The filing portrays AI compute expansion as a **core, capital-intensive strategic initiative** that is still in an early, high-investment phase. While the AI segment is already generating revenue and has secured certain commercial compute contracts, the company emphasizes a **multi-year investment horizon** with no expectation of near-term profitability. The compute build-out is explicitly positioned as a **long-duration strategic investment** aimed at achieving AGI-scale infrastructure and unlocking future markets rather than delivering immediate returns.\n\n---\n\n### Development Status\n\n- **Terrestrial compute:** The company is actively deploying **gigawatt-scale AI compute infrastructure**, including facilities like the COLOSSUS II facility in Memphis. In 2025, AI segment R&D spending accelerated to **$5,064 million** (up from $1,176 million in 2024) to speed up Grok’s development. Capital expenditures for the AI segment alone reached **$7,723 million in Q1 2026**.\n- **Orbital AI compute:** The company plans to begin deploying **orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028**, with a long-term goal of launching **100 gigawatts of compute to space per year**. This is described as a unique capability leveraging reusable rockets and low-cost satellite manufacturing.\n- **Chip manufacturing:** The company has a strategic collaboration with Tesla and Intel to build **Terafab**, intended to be the world’s largest chip manufacturing facility, eventually targeting **one terawatt of annual compute production** capacity. This is in the planning stage, with specific projects subject to future agreements.\n- **Overall posture:** The filing repeatedly frames speed, scale, and vertical integration as competitive necessities. Infrastructure is described as **fundamentally constrained** for frontier AI, and massive compute is seen as a critical differentiator.\n\n---\n\n### Revenue Generation\n\n- The AI segment **does generate revenue**: $3,201 million in 2025 and $818 million in Q1 2026, primarily from AI consumer subscriptions, advertising on X, and likely early compute monetization.\n- Despite this revenue, the segment is **deeply unprofitable**. In 2025, it posted an operating loss of **$(6,355) million** and negative Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237) million**. In Q1 2026, the operating loss was **$(2,469) million** with Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(609) million**.\n- The filing explicitly states the AI segment has incurred **significant operating losses since inception** and that the company **may not achieve profitability** in this segment or may not sustain it if achieved. The commercial value proposition of frontier AI models is called **“largely unproven.”**\n\n---\n\n### Commercial Contracts\n\n- **Anthropic cloud services agreement (May 2026):** The company entered into a contract to provide **access to its compute capacity** for a monthly fee through May 2029, with capacity ramping at a reduced fee initially. This reflects the strategy to **monetize unused compute capacity**.\n- **Cursor partnership:** A coding/software development collaboration that is part of the company’s evolving commercial and technical strategies.\n- **Valor hardware lease (April 2026):** A five-year equipment lease for AI infrastructure hardware worth **$6,587 million** in undiscounted lease payments.\n- **Turbine acquisition (April 2026):** An asset purchase of mobile gas turbines for approximately **$2,000 million** to power data centers.\n- **Non-cancelable commitments:** As of the filing date, the company had **$25,451 million** in contractual commitments, **primarily related to AI infrastructure and third-party cloud capacity**, with the majority due in 2027 ($21,476 million).\n- The filing also notes an intent to **sell high‑performance compute capacity to a limited number of third‑party customers** while simultaneously using that capacity for internal model development.\n\n---\n\n### Near-Term Revenue vs. Long-Duration Strategic Investment\n\nThe prospectus unequivocally frames AI compute expansion as a **long-duration strategic investment**, not a near-term profit play:\n\n- The company states it **“expect[s] a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.”**\n- It acknowledges that **capital expenditures will continue to increase for the foreseeable future** and that the company may **“prioritize long‑term growth over near‑term financial performance,”** which could result in **periods of reduced profitability or increased losses**.\n- The risks section warns that the **returns on AI investments may not be adequate to justify the capital deployed** and that **scaling laws may not hold**, potentially undermining the strategy.\n- Even the 2025 revenue of $3.2 billion is dwarfed by operating losses of $6.4 billion and massive capex, reinforcing that current revenue is incidental to the investment phase rather than indicative of an established, profitable business.\n\n**Bottom line:** The AI compute expansion is a **nascent, loss-making endeavor** with some early commercial contracts and revenue, but the filing is clear that it is a **long-term strategic bet** on AGI, orbital compute, and vertical integration—with no assurance of near-term profitability and a deliberately long investment runway.',
