million** | AI solutions & infrastructure up **$465 million** (subscriptions up **$365 million**, data licensing up **$88 million**); advertising up $116 million. | Total AI revenue +22.2% YoY |\n| **Q1 2026** | **$818 million** | AI solutions & infrastructure up **$191 million** (Grok & X subscriptions up **$177 million**, data licensing up **$12 million**); advertising **down $100 million**. | Total AI revenue +12.5% vs. Q1 2025 |\n\nThus, **Grok subscriptions are the fastest‑growing near‑term revenue driver**, while advertising on X provides scale but can be volatile.\n\n**3. Compute Monetisation (External)**\nThe filing mentions an evolving, non‑trivial effort to **monetise unused compute capacity** through “cloud compute services agreements with Anthropic.” However, this is presented as a parallel, early‑stage strategy that creates operational complexity and demands significant management attention; it is **not yet a material, stable revenue line** in the same way subscriptions and advertising are.\n\n### The Long‑Duration AI Compute Infrastructure Buildout\n\nThe AI segment is in an **early, massively investment‑heavy phase**. The company is building **gigawatt‑scale AI compute infrastructure** (including the COLOSSUS II facility in Memphis and plans for orbital compute) to support Grok’s development and future AGI capabilities. Key financial indicators of this buildout:\n\n- **Capex:** AI segment capital expenditures were **$7,723 million in Q1 2026 alone** (and $7.7 billion+ implied for FY2025 as well).\n- **R&D:** AI segment R&D expense surged to **$5,064 million in FY2025** (vs. $1,176 million in 2024), driven by *depreciation of GPU hardware* and cloud/data‑center infrastructure costs as the company expands AI data centers. In Q1 2026, AI R&D increased by **$1,471 million** YoY largely for the same reasons.\n- **Cost of Revenue:** AI cost of revenue jumped **$491 million in FY2025** (29.1%) due to higher infrastructure/cloud computing costs tied to subscriber growth. Q1 2026 saw a more modest $5 million increase, but the filing expects cost of revenue to “increase in absolute dollars as we grow our revenue” while decreasing as a percentage of revenue over time as products monetise.\n- **Segment Profitability:** The segment is deeply unprofitable because of this investment:\n  - FY2025: Loss from operations **$(6,355) million**, Segment Adjusted EBITDA **$(1,237) million**.\n  - Q1 2026: Loss from operations **$(2,469) million**, Segment Adjusted EBITDA **$(609) million**.\n\n### How Near‑Term Revenue and Long‑Term Buildout Relate\n\nThe filing is explicit that **current revenue (advertising, subscriptions, licensing) does not cover the enormous infrastructure costs**, and the company intends it that way. The strategy states:\n\n> “We plan to prioritize growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure.” … “We believe speed is a competitive advantage, and periodically we decide to increase and accelerate our investments. … As a result, our operating results, margins and profitability may fluctuate from period to period as we continue to prioritize execution speed, capacity expansion, and technological leadership over near‑term margin optimization.”\n\nThus, the near‑term AI revenues—particularly Grok subscriptions, which are scaling quickly—are viewed as an early proof point and a mechanism to eventually monetise the user base, but **the financial model is dominated by the buildout of compute capacity that is expected to unlock AGI and massive future demand**. The filing even notes that “without large‑scale, power‑efficient infrastructure, AGI cannot be deployed broadly or economically—making such infrastructure a critical strategic differentiator.” Long‑term, the company expects to monetise the compute through multiple channels: consumer subscriptions, enterprise Grok deployments, compute‑as‑a‑service (e.g., Anthropic deal), and advertising—but all of that hinges on first owning the infrastructure at unprecedented scale.',
