        output='Based on the filing excerpts, the company plans to allocate the net proceeds from its initial public offering (IPO) to several growth-oriented, capital-intensive initiatives. The core statement in the “Use of Proceeds” section reads:\n\n> “We intend to use the net proceeds from this offering to fund our growth strategy, including the expansion of our AI compute infrastructure, enhancements to our launch infrastructure and launch vehicles, increases in the scale and capacity of our satellite constellations, and any remaining amounts for general corporate purposes.”\n\nHowever, there is a separate, mandatory requirement tied to existing debt. A later section detailing the SpaceX Bridge Loan states that the company **must apply an amount equal to the net proceeds of a qualified IPO (including this offering) to repay outstanding borrowings under that loan**. This suggests that a portion (or potentially all) of the IPO proceeds will first be used to satisfy that obligation, and only the remainder, if any, will be deployed for the stated growth investments. The “Use of Proceeds” description likely reflects the intended allocation *after* that mandatory repayment, although the exact breakdown is not specified.\n\n### How the allocation reveals near‑term versus long‑duration priorities\n\nThe planned spending pattern is overwhelmingly oriented toward **long‑duration, infrastructure‑heavy projects** rather than near‑term profitability. Several elements make this clear:\n\n1. **Multi‑year investment horizons** – The filing repeatedly notes that the AI segment, satellite constellations, and launch‑vehicle development require substantial capital over many years before delivering returns. For example, the AI segment is described as having a “multi‑year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.” Similarly, Starship (a next‑generation launch vehicle) consumed $3,004 million in R&D in 2025 alone and is expected to require significant further investment.\n\n2. **Prioritization of speed and technological leadership over margins** – In the business strategy preamble, the company explicitly states that it “may increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time, which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long‑term growth over near‑term financial performance.” It also emphasizes that speed is a competitive advantage and that it will continue “prioritizing execution speed, capacity expansion, and technological leadership over near‑term margin optimization.” This signals that IPO capital will be used to push aggressively into frontier projects (AI compute, orbital AI, lunar infrastructure) even at the cost of short‑term profitability.\n\n3. **Nature of the assets being built** – The proceeds are earmarked for *base‑layer infrastructure*: AI compute facilities (GPUs, data centers), launch vehicles, and satellite constellations. These are foundational assets that, once deployed, are expected to unlock enormous future addressable markets (a $26.5 trillion AI market is cited), but they require years of construction and scaling. This contrasts with a near‑term focus on, say, marketing or short‑term revenue optimization.\n\n4. **Near‑term revenue drivers are supported differently** – While the company mentions a near‑term goal of growing Starlink Broadband subscribers (10.3 million subscribers as of March 2026) and monetizing the existing AI user base, those efforts are largely funded by existing operational cash flows and existing liquidity ($15.9 billion in cash and equivalents, $7.8 billion in short‑term marketable securities). The IPO proceeds are additionally directed at *expanding* the underlying capacity that will support those services in the future, not at immediate sales or margin gains.\n\n5. **Management flexibility and the debt repayment overhang** – The filing warns that “management will have significant flexibility in applying the net proceeds,” and the timing of expenditures will depend on “cash flows and the anticipated growth of our business.” This discretion, combined with the possibility that a large share of proceeds must first repay the Bridge Loan, means the near‑term deployment may initially be constrained by the debt obligation. Once any residual cash is available, it will flow toward the long‑term capital projects listed.\n\nIn summary, the filing signals that while the company has near‑term growth objectives (especially in Connectivity subscribers), the IPO proceeds are targeted at **long‑duration, competitive‑moat‑building infrastructure**—AI compute, advanced space systems, and satellite capacity—that will not contribute to profits for years. This reinforces a strategic posture of accepting losses today to pursue outsized, multi‑decade market opportunities.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=42.672,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
