        output='The filing describes Starlink Direct-to-Cell (marketed as “Starlink Mobile”) as an operational satellite-to-mobile service that uses a dedicated constellation of approximately **650 V1 Mobile satellites** in low‑Earth orbit. These satellites provide **light data, SMS, and over‑the‑top voice services (e.g., WhatsApp, FaceTime)** directly to unmodified LTE handsets. The service is commercially available in **~30 countries**, serving **~7.4 million monthly unique devices** through partnerships with ~30 mobile network operators (MNOs). It is designed to eliminate mobile dead zones, and the company notes it has been used to support emergency communications after natural disasters.\n\n**Revenue generation**  \nYes, the V1 Mobile service is currently generating revenue. The filing classifies Starlink Mobile revenue under the **Enterprise & Government** line within the Connectivity segment. In the Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 results, the company specifically highlights that **mobile connectivity business growth contributed $85 million** to the increase in enterprise and government revenue. The business model charges MNOs either a fixed fee or a per‑mobile‑user fee, which is typically passed through to end customers. Deferred revenue for mobile services is also recorded, and the company notes that mobile connectivity agreements generally have multi‑year terms.\n\n**Relationship to V2 Mobile satellites**  \nV2 Mobile satellites are the **next‑generation** platform, designed to deliver **more comprehensive satellite‑to‑mobile services**, including broadband data, IoT connectivity, and 5G. They will be deployed beginning in **2027**, using **Starship** (Falcon rockets cannot launch V2 Mobile satellites). The V2 Mobile constellation, combined with the acquisition of EchoStar spectrum and optimized 5G protocols, is expected to increase capacity **by orders of magnitude** compared to the first‑generation V1 Mobile network. The filing makes clear that V1 Mobile is the current operational service, while V2 Mobile represents a major future upgrade that will enable “Gen2” services. The V2 Mobile satellites are not yet in orbit, and their deployment depends on Starship readiness, regulatory approvals, and the closing of the EchoStar spectrum transaction. In summary, V1 Mobile is the **first‑phase, revenue‑generating** direct‑to‑cell network, and V2 Mobile is the planned **high‑capacity successor** that will significantly expand the service’s capabilities.',
