imelines.\n\n---\n\n## Implications for Execution and Monetization Timing\n\n### 1. The Funding Flywheel Is Operational but Stretched\n\nThe company\'s capital-allocation model follows a deliberate sequence: Falcon 9/Heavy cash flows funded Starlink; Falcon + Starlink cash flows now fund Starship and AI compute. This flywheel is visible in the numbers: the Space and Connectivity segments together "contributed the substantial majority of our consolidated revenue" with Connectivity alone generating $7,168 million in Segment Adjusted EBITDA in FY2025. However, the flywheel is under strain—combined Space segment operating losses (driven by Starship R&D) and AI segment operating losses totaled approximately $(7,012) million in FY2025, consuming essentially all of Connectivity\'s operating profit.\n\n### 2. Monetization Timing Is Highly Stratified\n\n| Initiative | Earliest Revenue Impact | Nature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Falcon 9 / Heavy | Current | Mature, cash-generative |\n| Starlink Broadband (existing) | Current | Scaling profitably |\n| V1 Mobile (D2C) | Current | Early revenue, scaling |\n| Grok / X subscriptions | Current | Growing but loss-making |\n| V3 Starlink Satellites | H2 2026 | Imminent revenue scaling |\n| Starship (initial payloads) | 2026 (milestone only) | No revenue until commercialization |\n| V2 Mobile (Gen2) | 2027+ | Multi-year ramp |\n| Orbital AI Compute | 2028+ | Speculative |\n| Terafab | Undetermined | Concept-stage |\n\n### 3. The AI Segment Embeds a Fundamental Tension\n\nThe AI segment is the most analytically complex: it generates $3.2 billion in near-term revenue (primarily subscriptions and advertising) but consumed $7.7 billion in quarterly capex and posted a $6.4 billion operating loss in FY2025. Management frames this as intentional—"we continue to prioritize execution speed, capacity expansion, and technological leadership over near-term margin optimization." The May 2026 Anthropic cloud-services agreement and the monetization of unuse